article.headline: Sun rise to first in the East
article.linkText: Sun edge Fever in OT for sixth straight victory
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- The Connecticut Sun seemed to solidify
their hold on last place in the WNBA's Eastern Conference about
three weeks ago when they dropped a decision to Charlotte for their
fifth loss in six games.

But Connecticut hasn't lost since, and Nykesha Sales helped made
sure that last place is now just a distant memory.

Sales faked out two defenders and sank a jumper from just inside
the 3-point line at the buzzer in overtime to lift Connecticut to a
79-77 win over the Indiana Fever on Tuesday night.

It was the sixth straight win for the Sun, now in first place in
the WNBA's Eastern Conference.

"I think we just have that mentality that every team we play,
we want to win," Sales said. "I think it's our reward to be in
first place. I don't think it's going to change our attitude at
all."

The Fever outrebounded the Sun 43-21 and never trailed until
Sales' game-winning shot.

"I guess that's why you play 40 or 45 minutes," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said. "To be honest, I thought Indiana played great
tonight, but at every timeout, we said, `Try to find some way to
hang in there.' "

That's just what the Sun did.

Indiana held a 67-56 lead with 3:20 left in the second half, but
Lindsay Whalen led a 14-3 run. Whalen had seven points in the run
and could have sealed the win in regulation, but she missed a
tie-breaking free throw with 8.4 seconds left.

Indiana had a chance to close out the Sun in regulation, but
Tamika Catchings missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer, and the game
went into overtime.

"I thought it was in," Whalen said of her free throw. "It
looked good. When it front-rimmed, I said, `For real?' Then I just
said, `OK, then we have to get a stop.' And then that 3 by Tamika
almost went in and my heart almost stopped."

The two teams traded baskets in the overtime before Stephanie
White's 3-pointer from the left corner with 1:02 left gave the
Fever a 77-74 lead.

Then Sales took over.

With 36.1 seconds left in overtime, she lofted a high-arching
3-point shot that hit nothing but net and tied the game at 77-77.

After Kelly Miller missed a jumper for Indiana, the Fever's
Natalie Williams was called for a foul as she reached for the
rebound, setting up a final chance for the Sun. Sales made it
count.

"We did many things right tonight," Fever coach Brian Winters
said. "There are some things that we need to do to get better.
We're still a young team. We need to learn how to close things out
better. Tamika had a chance to win the game for us. Sales made the
game-winning shot instead."

Sales led the Sun with 21 points. Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 20
points and five rebounds, while Whalen added 16 points and 10
assists.

Catchings led the Fever with 24 points and eight rebounds, while
Miller had 20 points. Williams added 16 points and 15 rebounds.

"We need to overcome this," Catchings said. "We need to get
mentally tougher."
